 I must check about trailing underscores in Checkstyle, and while the rule about test coverage says to separate active classes, using stubs is good. Though we shouldn’t use reflection unless necessary, I’m wondering about importing Method for public API. Also, internal packages like \\\"freemarker.debug.impl\\\" might not comply with rules, so I'll need to refine that last point.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating RemoteRef integration**\\n\\nI’m considering whether using RemoteRef custom might be too low-level since it’s not focused on behavioral integration with external libraries. The role requires high-coverage integration testing. The active class is an RMI-generated stub, so integration through Java RMI could be more fitting, though it adds complexity. The tests already start a debug server, and I could introduce a public API test for the active class. Maybe naming it \\\"generatedRmiStubResolvesDebugModelMethodsBeforeForwardingCalls\\\" could enhance robustness and clarity.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting test metadata setup**\\n\\nI’m looking at the statement \\\"Tests should execute under Native Image by default,\\\" which suggests that the final test suite should pass natively with the current metadata. I’m wondering if failing tests could be due to the absence of metadata. I think it’s important to inspect how the tests set up that metadata. Maybe I should search to see if there's any test-only metadata that gets generated.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_FEAvN58cebFeOEna8hcpNdMX|fc_00238142b910f31d0169f4945ecff48197b255753e903f490a", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/org.freemarker/freemarker/2.3.31 -maxdepth 2 -type f -name '*metadata*' -o -name 'reflect-config.json' -o -name 'resource-config.json' -o -name 'user-code-filter.json' -print"}, "partialJson": "{\"command\":\"find tests/src/org.freemarker/freemarker/2.3.31 -maxdepth 2 -type f -name '*metadata*' -o -name 'reflect-config.