XEm0CFyTAVoM2cYMT0F-DYvsa7NIoYiZSVtIV4tI-wRof6O4xZ5inkkSoBLdSK4zN5A9BWNJNj-Y_U0p_6ZvpyTWQ3zoU7Xc7-ZIok8Vhi-rm0V6bRa7A2F4xKrPFZoccCpL21FYKBjtpbYVmM9iidPVz4IjEjgcaiWWfSISGzJT1mbg6VsFApS5weLEZbhUoJbJPIU8e3LhsXLBALmdiumL1nlYZwnjlPx2KHxDJs5uarJztuU8FwsM-9XzElyc244cTayyfVzZ059XJn1UFXriw6BEA4tWI437vgh16cCfF4Y42lTZXbpRouG2VRbl5Zr\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing Graal initialization**\\n\\nI'm considering how Graal initializes classes at build time. If there's a direct class reference, could it be that the class initializer runs during the build? But, if there's dynamic access from a JVM agent after tests, maybe that’s not considered Native. The user mentioned attempts used two edits, so I need to change my strategy. Perhaps calls are dead due to static fields not being null before the class initializer? There could be more to the compatibility code with the modern JDK. I wonder if the coverage tool ignores errors during initialization.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test resources and initialization**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether I need to add test resources for native-image metadata to enforce runtime initialization. But the task focuses on tests. I could consider adding a build argument to initialize at runtime for the specific RmiDebugModelImpl_Stub class. However, my instructions only allow me to modify opens and exports in build.gradle, so that's off the table. Creating a custom ClassLoader might load a fresh version of the freemarker jar, but I wonder about dynamic-access reports. Would the target class name stay the same if loaded differently?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating code structure**\\n\\nI'm thinking I might not need the RecordingRemoteRef or the imports, just simplifying things. While previous direct stub calls might not provide coverage, maybe I should leave them in for now. I'll consider importing the class as a custom loader instead of referencing the active class directly.